{"questionId":"32521439","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A large sample of carp from the lake is studied. The length of each fish is measured and recorded correct to the nearest <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cm</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><div class=\"qb-leaf-part\" data-part=\"0\"><p>Consider a random sample of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>100</mn></math> carp from the lake.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-part\" data-part=\"1\"><p>Find the expected number of carp with lengths between <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>40</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cm</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>56</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cm</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-part\" data-part=\"2\"><p>Find the probability that in this sample, exactly <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>95</mn></math> carp have a length between <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>40</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cm</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>56</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cm</mi></math>.</p></div></div>","markschemeHtml":"<div class=\"qb-ms-part\" data-part=\"0\"><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>40</mn><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>L</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>56</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>902149</mn><mo>…</mo></math>&nbsp;(may be seen in part (ii))&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>attempts to find <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>100</mn><mo>×</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>40</mn><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>L</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>56</mn></mrow></mfenced></math> with their probability&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathM